  "prompt": "What is  EDNOS? What are some examples?",
  "response": "**EDNOS** stands for **Eating Disorder Not Otherwise Specified**. It is a diagnostic category used in the **DSM-IV** (Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, 4th Edition) to describe eating disorders that do not meet the full criteria for specific disorders like anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, or binge-eating disorder. In the **DSM-5**, which is the current edition, this category has been replaced with **Other Specified Feeding or Eating Disorder (OSFED)** and **Unspecified Feeding or Eating Disorder (UFED)**.\n\n### Examples of EDNOS (or OSFED/UFED) include:\n1. **Atypical Anorexia Nervosa**  \n   - The individual meets all criteria for anorexia nervosa except their weight remains within or above the normal range.\n\n2. **Subthreshold Bulimia Nervosa**  \n   - Binge eating and inappropriate compensatory behaviors occur less frequently than the DSM-5 threshold (e.g., less than once a week or for less than three months).\n\n3. **Subthreshold Binge-Eating Disorder (BED)**  \n   - Binge eating occurs less frequently than the DSM-5 threshold (e.g., less than once a week or for less than three months).\n\n4. **Purging Disorder**  \n   - The individual engages in purging behaviors (e.g., vomiting, laxative use) without binge eating.\n\n5. **Night Eating Syndrome**  \n   - Recurrent episodes of night eating, such as eating after awakening from sleep or excessive food consumption after the evening meal.\n\n6. **Other Atypical Presentations**  \n   - Conditions that resemble eating disorders but do not fit neatly into other categories (e.g., restrictive eating without fear of weight gain or body image disturbance).\n\n### Key Points:\n- EDNOS/OSFED is a clinically significant condition and can still cause severe physical and emotional harm.\n- It is important to seek professional help for proper diagnosis and treatment, as these disorders can be just as serious as more well-known eating disorders.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
